{"cursor":"3108","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":" light by the Infrared Astronomical Satellite (IRAS).]]\n\n'Comet IRASâArakiâAlcock' (formal designation 'C/1983 H1', formerly '1983 VII')\nis a long-period comet that, in 1983, made the closest approach to Earth, about\n, of any comet in 200 years; only Lexell's Comet, in 1770, and 55P/Tempel-\nTuttle, in 1366, are thought to have come closer. (The small comet P/1999 J6 (SOHO) passed about from Earth on 1999-Jun-\n12.)\n\nThe comet was named after its discoverers â the Infrared Astronomical Satellite\nand two amateur astronomers, the highly-respected George Alcock of the United\nKingdom and Genichi Araki of Japan (both men were schoolteachers by profession,\nalthough Alcock was retired). Alcock had made his discovery simply by observing\nthrough the window of his home, using binoculars. '[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/1081747.stm Obituary of George\nAlcock]' BBC News, 21-12/2000 '[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,953909,00.html\nOutbreak of Comet Fever]', TIME Magazine, 23-05-83. \"I've discovered a wonderful\nstar,\" commented Araki, \"Now I've got to discover a wonderful wife.\"\n\nDuring the closest approach the comet appeared as a circular cloud about the\nsize of the full moon, having no discernible tail, and shining at a naked eye\nmagnitude of 3-4. It swept across the sky at an incredible speed of some 30\ndegrees per day.\n\nIt is a long-period comet, with an orbital period of around 964 years, and is\nthe parent comet of the minor Eta Lyrid meteor shower. '[http://meteorshowersonline.com/showers/eta_lyrids.html Eta\nLyrids]', Meteor Showers Online, accessed 21-11-08 This shower's radiant\nlies between Vega and Cygnus and produces 1 or 2 meteors an hour in mid-May with\na peak between May 9 and May 11.\n","linknr":130,"url":"Comet_IRAS–Araki–Alcock","recorded":1372154903,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Comet_IRAS%E2%80%93Araki%E2%80%93Alcock&action=edit","/w/index.p